"sba","marks":1,"options":["Limbic system","Thyroid gland","Hepatic tissue","Hypothalamus","Placental tissue"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehypothalamus\u003C/strong\u003E is directly affected by glucocorticoids during early fetal development. This interaction programs the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis and establishes lifelong patterns of stress response and cortisol regulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less directly affected:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimbic system\u003C/strong\u003E - While involved in emotional responses to stress, it is not directly programmed by early glucocorticoid exposure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid gland\u003C/strong\u003E - Although influenced by glucocorticoids, it is not a primary target during early development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepatic tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - While responsive to glucocorticoids throughout life, it is not directly programmed during early development\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental tissue\u003C/strong\u003E - Acts more as a barrier and modifier of glucocorticoid exposure rather than a direct target\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe direct programming of the hypothalamus by glucocorticoids establishes appropriate feedback mechanisms and setpoints for cortisol regulation that persist throughout life.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glucocorticoids directly affect fetal hypothalamic development during early embryogenesis","Glucocorticoids program the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal (HPA) axis feedback mechanisms during fetal development","Early glucocorticoid exposure sets lifelong stress response patterns through hypothalamic programming"],"references":["Melmed, S., Polonsky, K. S., Larsen, P. R., \u0026 Kronenberg, H. M. (2015). Williams textbook of endocrinology E-Book. 